WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.990 align:middle line:90%


00:00:06.990 --> 00:00:10.940 align:middle line:84%
>> In the United States alone,
there are over 200 million cell

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:11.870 align:middle line:90%
phones in use.

00:00:11.870 --> 00:00:15.810 align:middle line:84%
Globally, this figure
stands at 4.77 billion

00:00:15.810 --> 00:00:22.130 align:middle line:84%
and is expected to reach
6.1 billion by 2020.

00:00:22.130 --> 00:00:27.100 align:middle line:84%
>> Prior to 1984, wireless
technology was only used

00:00:27.100 --> 00:00:28.940 align:middle line:90%
in the military.

00:00:28.940 --> 00:00:33.920 align:middle line:84%
And in 1984 was the first move
to take wireless technology

00:00:33.920 --> 00:00:36.110 align:middle line:90%
into the consumer environment.

00:00:36.110 --> 00:00:39.140 align:middle line:84%
Cell phones, at the
time, they were excluded

00:00:39.140 --> 00:00:40.760 align:middle line:90%
from any premarket testing.

00:00:40.760 --> 00:00:43.610 align:middle line:84%
So they came onto the market
without any safety testing

00:00:43.610 --> 00:00:44.874 align:middle line:90%
at all.

00:00:44.874 --> 00:00:52.329 align:middle line:10%
[JUMBLE OF CELL-PHONE RINGTONES]

00:00:52.329 --> 00:01:07.740 align:middle line:90%


00:01:07.740 --> 00:01:09.660 align:middle line:84%
>> When we evolved
on the planet,

00:01:09.660 --> 00:01:13.830 align:middle line:84%
there was no microwave radiation
other than this infinitesimal

00:01:13.830 --> 00:01:15.110 align:middle line:90%
amount.

00:01:15.110 --> 00:01:18.640 align:middle line:10%
And what we have added
today is 1 billion times

00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:22.440 align:middle line:10%
more microwave radiation.

00:01:22.440 --> 00:01:24.000 align:middle line:84%
Our bodies didn't
evolve with it,

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:25.900 align:middle line:84%
and we have no
protection against it.

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:29.340 align:middle line:84%
So it's invisible,
but it's a very real

00:01:29.340 --> 00:01:32.400 align:middle line:90%
environmental pollutant.

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:37.110 align:middle line:10%
>> If I ask you how much more
such radiation does penetrate

00:01:37.110 --> 00:01:42.060 align:middle line:10%
your body today, compared
to, like, 10 years ago,

00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:44.010 align:middle line:10%
is it twice as much?

00:01:44.010 --> 00:01:45.630 align:middle line:90%
Three times as much?

00:01:45.630 --> 00:01:48.420 align:middle line:84%
No, it's a quintillion
times more.

00:01:48.420 --> 00:01:52.850 align:middle line:90%
That's a 1 with 18 zeros.

00:01:52.850 --> 00:01:56.230 align:middle line:10%
>> EMF, or
ElectroMagnetic Fields,

00:01:56.230 --> 00:01:58.750 align:middle line:10%
are invisible forms of
energy, often referred

00:01:58.750 --> 00:02:00.310 align:middle line:10%
to as "radiation."

00:02:00.310 --> 00:02:02.620 align:middle line:84%
They are associated with
the use of electrical power

00:02:02.620 --> 00:02:05.485 align:middle line:84%
in various technologies,
including wireless devices.

00:02:05.485 --> 00:02:12.760 align:middle line:90%


00:02:12.760 --> 00:02:15.430 align:middle line:90%
>> We are electrical in nature.

00:02:15.430 --> 00:02:18.730 align:middle line:84%
We are made of the same
stuff as everything else.

00:02:18.730 --> 00:02:20.980 align:middle line:10%
We are made of
atoms, and atoms are

00:02:20.980 --> 00:02:24.040 align:middle line:10%
made of electrons, which are
negatively charged, protons

00:02:24.040 --> 00:02:25.540 align:middle line:10%
that are positively charged.

00:02:25.540 --> 00:02:28.850 align:middle line:84%
And we react to
electromagnetic fields.

00:02:28.850 --> 00:02:33.620 align:middle line:84%
So it's not surprising that we
respond to all kinds of things.

00:02:33.620 --> 00:02:35.876 align:middle line:10%
>> So there's various
kinds of radiation.

00:02:35.876 --> 00:02:37.500 align:middle line:10%
And one of the
distinctions that's made

00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:42.670 align:middle line:10%
is between ionizing radiation
and nonionizing radiation.

00:02:42.670 --> 00:02:45.070 align:middle line:84%
That distinction
reflects the energy

00:02:45.070 --> 00:02:49.150 align:middle line:84%
that the radiation delivers and
whether it breaks up molecules

00:02:49.150 --> 00:02:51.540 align:middle line:90%
as it passes through tissues.

00:02:51.540 --> 00:02:54.160 align:middle line:84%
>> The electromagnetic spectrum
measures different levels

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:56.080 align:middle line:90%
of radiation.

00:02:56.080 --> 00:02:59.530 align:middle line:84%
Nonionizing radiation
emits lower energy,

00:02:59.530 --> 00:03:02.620 align:middle line:84%
while ionizing radiation
emits higher energy.

00:03:02.620 --> 00:03:04.740 align:middle line:84%
The higher the energy,
the more dangerous

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:06.890 align:middle line:90%
it becomes for our health.

00:03:06.890 --> 00:03:09.040 align:middle line:84%
Most people are able to
tolerate lower energy

00:03:09.040 --> 00:03:13.300 align:middle line:84%
fields, such as AM/FM
radio, for example.

00:03:13.300 --> 00:03:17.020 align:middle line:10%
Wireless technology emits
nonionizing radiation

00:03:17.020 --> 00:03:19.240 align:middle line:10%
known as "radio frequencies."

00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:21.540 align:middle line:84%
Regulatory agencies
consider these emissions

00:03:21.540 --> 00:03:25.450 align:middle line:84%
safe for short periods of
time, but increased exposure

00:03:25.450 --> 00:03:27.355 align:middle line:84%
could have dangerous
biological effects.

00:03:27.355 --> 00:03:30.640 align:middle line:90%


00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:33.060 align:middle line:10%
The light from the
sun causes sunburn,

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:35.410 align:middle line:10%
or skin cancer in some.

00:03:35.410 --> 00:03:38.020 align:middle line:10%
Overexposure to
X-rays and cosmic rays

00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:40.796 align:middle line:10%
are, [HISSING INHALE]
um, dangerous.

00:03:40.796 --> 00:03:48.236 align:middle line:90%


00:03:48.236 --> 00:03:51.290 align:middle line:84%
>> Where there's scientific
uncertainty and a need

00:03:51.290 --> 00:03:57.230 align:middle line:84%
for research is how nonionizing
radiation might cause some

00:03:57.230 --> 00:03:58.830 align:middle line:84%
of the diseases
that are of concern,

00:03:58.830 --> 00:04:01.850 align:middle line:84%
some of the diseases we've
seen epidemiologically.

00:04:01.850 --> 00:04:04.410 align:middle line:84%
So, yes, we know that
there's a potential to heat,

00:04:04.410 --> 00:04:06.410 align:middle line:84%
and then there are questions
about whether there

00:04:06.410 --> 00:04:09.748 align:middle line:90%
are other potential mechanisms.

00:04:09.748 --> 00:04:19.709 align:middle line:90%


00:04:19.709 --> 00:04:23.040 align:middle line:84%
>> As a society, we are very
fond of things that make life

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:25.380 align:middle line:90%
easier or more enjoyable--

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:27.420 align:middle line:84%
anything that provides
relief from the stress

00:04:27.420 --> 00:04:29.130 align:middle line:90%
of everyday life.

00:04:29.130 --> 00:04:31.710 align:middle line:84%
But history has shown our
enjoyment and dependence

00:04:31.710 --> 00:04:35.250 align:middle line:84%
on these things can blind
us to their adverse effects

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:38.720 align:middle line:84%
and influence us to ignore
obvious warning signs.

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:41.730 align:middle line:10%
>> Could where you carry your
cell phone make you sick?

00:04:41.730 --> 00:04:45.060 align:middle line:10%
Some doctors say they're seeing
evidence of cancer that could

00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:47.130 align:middle line:10%
be linked to mobile phones.

00:04:47.130 --> 00:04:49.560 align:middle line:10%
>> It's convenient,
say many young women.

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:51.930 align:middle line:10%
>> It's probably the most
convenient place to put it,

00:04:51.930 --> 00:04:53.290 align:middle line:10%
especially when you go out.

00:04:53.290 --> 00:04:54.370 align:middle line:84%
You know, you put
your money on one--

00:04:54.370 --> 00:04:56.550 align:middle line:84%
[LAUGH] one breast and
your phone in the other.

00:04:56.550 --> 00:04:59.340 align:middle line:84%
>> If I'm wearing a dress ever,
I usually just slip it, like,

00:04:59.340 --> 00:05:02.250 align:middle line:84%
in the straps or
down in the center.

00:05:02.250 --> 00:05:04.890 align:middle line:84%
>> I used to carry my
cell phone in my bra,

00:05:04.890 --> 00:05:07.570 align:middle line:84%
whenever I'd use a
Bluetooth headset,

00:05:07.570 --> 00:05:09.840 align:middle line:90%
because the connection was poor.

00:05:09.840 --> 00:05:11.910 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, if it was
anything further away,

00:05:11.910 --> 00:05:14.130 align:middle line:84%
it would just--
wouldn't work well.

00:05:14.130 --> 00:05:16.350 align:middle line:84%
I don't have a family
history of cancer.

00:05:16.350 --> 00:05:18.630 align:middle line:84%
And so cancer was
nowhere on the radar,

00:05:18.630 --> 00:05:24.780 align:middle line:84%
as far as something that I
thought that I would ever

00:05:24.780 --> 00:05:26.040 align:middle line:90%
have to deal with in my life.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:28.650 align:middle line:90%


00:05:28.650 --> 00:05:30.510 align:middle line:84%
I was diagnosed
with breast cancer,

00:05:30.510 --> 00:05:32.790 align:middle line:84%
and they found
five tumors, pretty

00:05:32.790 --> 00:05:36.150 align:middle line:84%
much in the footprint of
where the phone used to sit,

00:05:36.150 --> 00:05:40.800 align:middle line:84%
right in the kind of
center area of my chest.

00:05:40.800 --> 00:05:44.400 align:middle line:84%
The morning of my mammogram and
ultrasound, my husband and I

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:47.040 align:middle line:90%
were trying to locate the lump.

00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:49.170 align:middle line:84%
We were going to mark
it with a Sharpie,

00:05:49.170 --> 00:05:52.470 align:middle line:84%
so that it would be easy to
point out to the person who

00:05:52.470 --> 00:05:53.940 align:middle line:90%
was going to do the testing.

00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:56.930 align:middle line:84%
And I pointed to one
spot, and he said--

00:05:56.930 --> 00:05:58.560 align:middle line:84%
and then he was
trying to feel it.

00:05:58.560 --> 00:05:59.250 align:middle line:84%
And he said, no,
no, it's right here.

00:05:59.250 --> 00:06:01.290 align:middle line:84%
And no, I said, it's right
here-- not realizing,

00:06:01.290 --> 00:06:02.340 align:middle line:84%
at the time, that
we had actually

00:06:02.340 --> 00:06:03.810 align:middle line:90%
found another one that morning.

00:06:03.810 --> 00:06:07.650 align:middle line:90%


00:06:07.650 --> 00:06:10.680 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm not the kind of person
that's an advocate for these

00:06:10.680 --> 00:06:11.680 align:middle line:90%
unusual problems.

00:06:11.680 --> 00:06:12.972 align:middle line:90%
I don't go onto crazy diets.

00:06:12.972 --> 00:06:14.430 align:middle line:84%
I don't worry about
the environment

00:06:14.430 --> 00:06:15.870 align:middle line:90%
maybe as much as I should.

00:06:15.870 --> 00:06:18.480 align:middle line:10%
I really am a focused physician.

00:06:18.480 --> 00:06:20.680 align:middle line:10%
But when Donna came
in with her case,

00:06:20.680 --> 00:06:21.810 align:middle line:10%
it kind of opened my mind.

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:23.559 align:middle line:84%
It didn't convince me
there was a problem,

00:06:23.559 --> 00:06:26.580 align:middle line:84%
but I remember sitting, very
clearly looking at her slides

00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:28.230 align:middle line:90%
with the pathologist.

00:06:28.230 --> 00:06:30.080 align:middle line:84%
And I said, well, how
many tumors are there

00:06:30.080 --> 00:06:30.690 align:middle line:90%
in this breast?

00:06:30.690 --> 00:06:32.065 align:middle line:84%
She said, well,
there's basically

00:06:32.065 --> 00:06:34.165 align:middle line:90%
three dominant tumors.

00:06:34.165 --> 00:06:37.860 align:middle line:84%
But it wasn't until we looked
at her mastectomy specimen

00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:40.560 align:middle line:84%
under the microscope
and saw what wasn't just

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:44.140 align:middle line:84%
a single cancer, but it
was multiple cancers.

00:06:44.140 --> 00:06:47.010 align:middle line:84%
But it was very extensive,
in a very unusual pattern.

00:06:47.010 --> 00:06:48.870 align:middle line:84%
And that's when it
clicked with me.

00:06:48.870 --> 00:06:50.820 align:middle line:84%
I said, you know, I
don't remember seeing

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:52.260 align:middle line:90%
that pattern in anybody before.

00:06:52.260 --> 00:06:54.718 align:middle line:84%
And I remember her saying she
worried about her cell phone.

00:06:54.718 --> 00:06:56.970 align:middle line:90%
Could there be a connection?

00:06:56.970 --> 00:06:59.280 align:middle line:84%
>> The wireless industry
denies there's a problem,

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:02.700 align:middle line:84%
citing a lack of scientific
evidence that cell phones cause

00:07:02.700 --> 00:07:03.694 align:middle line:90%
breast cancer.

00:07:03.694 --> 00:07:05.610 align:middle line:10%
>> There is no evidence,
but that's because we

00:07:05.610 --> 00:07:07.290 align:middle line:10%
haven't studied it.

00:07:07.290 --> 00:07:12.120 align:middle line:10%
>> We have cancer registries
in place that quite carefully

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:17.400 align:middle line:10%
track new cancers among
children and adults.

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:21.570 align:middle line:84%
They work with the hospitals,
the clinics, the pathologists

00:07:21.570 --> 00:07:24.030 align:middle line:90%
to identify each new case.

00:07:24.030 --> 00:07:25.740 align:middle line:84%
And this is to
help us understand

00:07:25.740 --> 00:07:28.830 align:middle line:84%
how much cancer there
is, what kinds there are,

00:07:28.830 --> 00:07:30.550 align:middle line:84%
and what directions
the rates are going.

00:07:30.550 --> 00:07:32.460 align:middle line:90%
Are they going up or down?

00:07:32.460 --> 00:07:35.100 align:middle line:84%
>> The question comes up, how
long would it take to prove

00:07:35.100 --> 00:07:38.640 align:middle line:84%
that cell phones could cause it,
based on the way we figured out

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:40.800 align:middle line:90%
smoking caused lung cancer?

00:07:40.800 --> 00:07:42.060 align:middle line:90%
And there's no database.

00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:44.735 align:middle line:84%
All this stuff takes
years to accumulate.

00:07:44.735 --> 00:07:46.110 align:middle line:84%
The doctors, by
and large, aren't

00:07:46.110 --> 00:07:48.150 align:middle line:84%
asking patients, you know,
did you put your cell

00:07:48.150 --> 00:07:48.960 align:middle line:90%
phone in your bra?

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:51.001 align:middle line:84%
Yes, a few of them are,
and I've had phone calls,

00:07:51.001 --> 00:07:53.940 align:middle line:84%
and I've had patients come to
me because their doctor made

00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:54.930 align:middle line:90%
the connection.

00:07:54.930 --> 00:07:58.060 align:middle line:84%
So it is happening, but it's
not like with lung cancer.

00:07:58.060 --> 00:08:00.300 align:middle line:84%
I think it may take
longer for cell phones

00:08:00.300 --> 00:08:03.799 align:middle line:84%
to accumulate enough
data to really prove

00:08:03.799 --> 00:08:05.340 align:middle line:84%
it's a risk factor
for breast cancer.

00:08:05.340 --> 00:08:23.420 align:middle line:90%


00:08:23.420 --> 00:08:26.080 align:middle line:84%
How is it that wireless
devices and Wi-Fi have

00:08:26.080 --> 00:08:29.860 align:middle line:84%
been able to permeate our daily
lives over the last 20 years

00:08:29.860 --> 00:08:31.450 align:middle line:84%
without the public
being made aware

00:08:31.450 --> 00:08:33.520 align:middle line:90%
of the associated dangers?

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:37.600 align:middle line:10%
>> So, back in 1984, the two
key agencies were the FDA

00:08:37.600 --> 00:08:43.000 align:middle line:10%
for the devices and the
EPA for the infrastructure.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.360 align:middle line:10%
>> The FDA, or Food and
Drug Administration,

00:08:46.360 --> 00:08:49.750 align:middle line:10%
was established to protect and
promote public health through

00:08:49.750 --> 00:08:54.430 align:middle line:10%
the regulation of the food,
tobacco, veterinary, cosmetic,

00:08:54.430 --> 00:08:57.220 align:middle line:10%
and pharmaceutical industries.

00:08:57.220 --> 00:09:00.520 align:middle line:10%
The EPA, or Environmental
Protection Agency,

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:02.470 align:middle line:10%
was created for the
purpose of protecting

00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:05.500 align:middle line:10%
human health and the environment
by writing and enforcing

00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:07.180 align:middle line:10%
regulations.

00:09:07.180 --> 00:09:09.640 align:middle line:84%
Neither agency had any
previous experience

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:14.810 align:middle line:84%
with the regulation or safety
testing of new technology.

00:09:14.810 --> 00:09:18.700 align:middle line:10%
>> Both of those agencies
preempted either premarket

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:21.100 align:middle line:10%
testing or postmarket
surveillance,

00:09:21.100 --> 00:09:24.640 align:middle line:10%
because, at the time, it was
felt that the power was so low

00:09:24.640 --> 00:09:27.550 align:middle line:10%
for cell-phone transmissions
that there could not be

00:09:27.550 --> 00:09:28.570 align:middle line:10%
heating.

00:09:28.570 --> 00:09:30.925 align:middle line:84%
And without heating there
could not be health effects.

00:09:30.925 --> 00:09:45.770 align:middle line:90%


00:09:45.770 --> 00:09:47.140 align:middle line:90%
>> My name is Jaimie.

00:09:47.140 --> 00:09:49.320 align:middle line:84%
I'm from Los
Angeles, California.

00:09:49.320 --> 00:09:50.840 align:middle line:90%
I'm a photographer.

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:54.390 align:middle line:90%
And I'm electrosensitive.

00:09:54.390 --> 00:09:57.870 align:middle line:84%
>> Electrohypersensitivity,
or electrosensitivity,

00:09:57.870 --> 00:10:00.480 align:middle line:84%
is the sensitivity to
electromagnetic fields

00:10:00.480 --> 00:10:02.640 align:middle line:90%
in the environment.

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:05.490 align:middle line:84%
>> I think when cell phones
first came out we'd have,

00:10:05.490 --> 00:10:07.860 align:middle line:84%
you know, the burning
feeling, the hot-ear syndrome,

00:10:07.860 --> 00:10:10.370 align:middle line:84%
kind of headache, but didn't
think anything about it,

00:10:10.370 --> 00:10:12.900 align:middle line:84%
because we were all told
they were awesome and safe.

00:10:12.900 --> 00:10:15.630 align:middle line:84%
Another aha moment was
when we had wireless.

00:10:15.630 --> 00:10:17.210 align:middle line:84%
Just watching movies
on the laptop,

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:18.330 align:middle line:90%
the symptoms would start--

00:10:18.330 --> 00:10:20.850 align:middle line:90%
headache, brain fog, itchy eyes.

00:10:20.850 --> 00:10:23.790 align:middle line:84%
I just thought maybe I'm
staring at the screen too long.

00:10:23.790 --> 00:10:28.800 align:middle line:84%
Electrohypersensitivity, or EHS,
is currently not a recognized

00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:30.930 align:middle line:90%
medical diagnosis.

00:10:30.930 --> 00:10:33.800 align:middle line:84%
Experts are still divided
as to its validity.

00:10:33.800 --> 00:10:35.460 align:middle line:84%
And the World
Health Organization

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:37.770 align:middle line:84%
claims there is no
diagnostic criteria

00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:41.490 align:middle line:84%
to link EHS to exposure
to electromagnetic fields

00:10:41.490 --> 00:10:44.730 align:middle line:90%
or microwave radiation.

00:10:44.730 --> 00:10:47.850 align:middle line:84%
>> I was diagnosed
with EHS in 2011.

00:10:47.850 --> 00:10:49.590 align:middle line:84%
>> And I became
electromagnetically

00:10:49.590 --> 00:10:52.380 align:middle line:90%
hypersensitive in 2009.

00:10:52.380 --> 00:10:55.920 align:middle line:84%
>> There are many symptoms,
but when I'm in a high EMF

00:10:55.920 --> 00:10:59.620 align:middle line:84%
environment or in a place
with a strong Wi-Fi,

00:10:59.620 --> 00:11:02.940 align:middle line:84%
first it starts off
with a burning sensation

00:11:02.940 --> 00:11:04.140 align:middle line:90%
in my forehead.

00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:06.130 align:middle line:90%
>> Dizziness, fatigue--

00:11:06.130 --> 00:11:08.580 align:middle line:90%
>> Pain in the back of my head.

00:11:08.580 --> 00:11:10.080 align:middle line:84%
>> Right in my neck,
and a headache.

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:10.879 align:middle line:90%
>> Headache--

00:11:10.879 --> 00:11:13.020 align:middle line:84%
>> And my muscles start
pulsing or vibrating.

00:11:13.020 --> 00:11:15.480 align:middle line:84%
>> --where I feel like
I'm going to throw up.

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:19.030 align:middle line:84%
>> Heart palpitations,
breathlessness, feeling faint.

00:11:19.030 --> 00:11:20.520 align:middle line:84%
>> I left my home
for three weeks,

00:11:20.520 --> 00:11:22.853 align:middle line:84%
and I didn't have a headache
the entire time I was gone.

00:11:22.853 --> 00:11:24.000 align:middle line:90%
I came back into my house.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:24.916 align:middle line:10%
My headaches returned.

00:11:24.916 --> 00:11:26.800 align:middle line:90%
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:29.490 align:middle line:84%
>> Microwave radiation is
the ultimate pollutant.

00:11:29.490 --> 00:11:33.240 align:middle line:84%
You can't see it, you can't
smell it, you can't hear it,

00:11:33.240 --> 00:11:35.190 align:middle line:90%
but you can feel it.

00:11:35.190 --> 00:11:58.130 align:middle line:90%


00:11:58.130 --> 00:12:00.760 align:middle line:10%
>> I think it's an interesting
area, too, for me personally,

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:05.830 align:middle line:10%
as a doctor, to learn more about
the electrosensitive syndrome.

00:12:05.830 --> 00:12:08.470 align:middle line:10%
And I would hope
that there would

00:12:08.470 --> 00:12:13.270 align:middle line:10%
be criteria for the diagnosis--
which we don't have today.

00:12:13.270 --> 00:12:15.940 align:middle line:84%
My hope is that this
should be recognized

00:12:15.940 --> 00:12:19.150 align:middle line:84%
as a medical disorder
and, as such,

00:12:19.150 --> 00:12:22.750 align:middle line:84%
get an international
code of diseases.

00:12:22.750 --> 00:12:24.640 align:middle line:84%
That's one thing
which is urgent.

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:27.650 align:middle line:84%
The other thing is to come up
with some kind of treatment

00:12:27.650 --> 00:12:28.450 align:middle line:90%
advice.

00:12:28.450 --> 00:12:33.530 align:middle line:84%
Because there are different
types of treatments.

00:12:33.530 --> 00:12:36.550 align:middle line:10%
>> There is an increasing
body of diagnostic tests

00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:40.390 align:middle line:10%
and guidelines that can
correlate the exposure

00:12:40.390 --> 00:12:44.710 align:middle line:10%
of a person to radiation and
the physiological effects quite

00:12:44.710 --> 00:12:45.980 align:middle line:10%
reliably.

00:12:45.980 --> 00:12:48.640 align:middle line:10%
Recently, Professor Dominique
Belpomme, from France,

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:52.360 align:middle line:10%
tested about 700 people who
suffer from electrosensitivity.

00:12:52.360 --> 00:12:55.540 align:middle line:84%
His study showed severe
damage such as damage

00:12:55.540 --> 00:12:57.790 align:middle line:84%
to the immune system,
to the nervous system,

00:12:57.790 --> 00:13:00.550 align:middle line:84%
and established
additional biomarkers

00:13:00.550 --> 00:13:03.000 align:middle line:84%
for the diagnosis of
electrosensitivity.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:07.700 align:middle line:90%


00:13:07.700 --> 00:13:10.100 align:middle line:84%
>> I became very involved
in the cell-phone,

00:13:10.100 --> 00:13:14.640 align:middle line:84%
brain-tumor issue in 2008, when
my husband was diagnosed with

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:15.440 align:middle line:90%
a brain tumor.

00:13:15.440 --> 00:13:19.940 align:middle line:90%


00:13:19.940 --> 00:13:22.940 align:middle line:84%
He had a grand mal seizure
in the middle of the night

00:13:22.940 --> 00:13:26.060 align:middle line:84%
and was rushed by ambulance
to our local hospital.

00:13:26.060 --> 00:13:28.760 align:middle line:84%
And within an hour they
had done a CT scan.

00:13:28.760 --> 00:13:34.610 align:middle line:84%
And they said he had a large
mass in his right frontal lobe.

00:13:34.610 --> 00:13:38.090 align:middle line:84%
He had to wait, though,
about two weeks for surgery.

00:13:38.090 --> 00:13:39.950 align:middle line:84%
And what was really
remarkable was

00:13:39.950 --> 00:13:42.820 align:middle line:84%
that our son had worked
for Senator Ted Kennedy.

00:13:42.820 --> 00:13:44.190 align:middle line:10%
He was an intern for him.

00:13:44.190 --> 00:13:47.130 align:middle line:10%
We've just learned, here,
in the last hour or so,

00:13:47.130 --> 00:13:49.170 align:middle line:10%
that Ted Kennedy
has a brain tumor.

00:13:49.170 --> 00:13:49.970 align:middle line:10%
That news--

00:13:49.970 --> 00:13:51.950 align:middle line:10%
>> So my son came
in, and he said Mom,

00:13:51.950 --> 00:13:53.480 align:middle line:10%
I have to talk to you about
something that's really

00:13:53.480 --> 00:13:54.350 align:middle line:10%
bothering me.

00:13:54.350 --> 00:13:56.190 align:middle line:84%
They think it was
his cell phone.

00:13:56.190 --> 00:13:59.360 align:middle line:84%
And I was just stunned,
because my husband was

00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:01.430 align:middle line:90%
a heavy user of a cell phone.

00:14:01.430 --> 00:14:04.940 align:middle line:84%
He always held it
to his right ear.

00:14:04.940 --> 00:14:08.310 align:middle line:84%
And his tumor grew, it was
his right frontal lobe.

00:14:08.310 --> 00:14:10.640 align:middle line:84%
I remember, that night, I
stayed up all night long,

00:14:10.640 --> 00:14:11.600 align:middle line:90%
searching the internet.

00:14:11.600 --> 00:14:15.740 align:middle line:84%
And I found all this information
that I had no idea existed.

00:14:15.740 --> 00:14:17.270 align:middle line:90%
And there were studies about it.

00:14:17.270 --> 00:14:19.040 align:middle line:84%
And there were
scientists in Sweden,

00:14:19.040 --> 00:14:20.750 align:middle line:84%
and there were other
people who were

00:14:20.750 --> 00:14:23.950 align:middle line:84%
talking about how cell phones
were causing brain tumors.

00:14:23.950 --> 00:14:27.330 align:middle line:84%
>> Today we're talking about
cell phones and brain cancer.

00:14:27.330 --> 00:14:29.420 align:middle line:84%
>> We don't know why
they're harmful, right?

00:14:29.420 --> 00:14:31.940 align:middle line:10%
>> Sheryl Crow was recently
diagnosed with a benign brain

00:14:31.940 --> 00:14:32.390 align:middle line:10%
tumor.

00:14:32.390 --> 00:14:33.770 align:middle line:10%
>> It's in my cell-phone area.

00:14:33.770 --> 00:14:37.200 align:middle line:10%
And there are doctors
that will confirm that.

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:39.680 align:middle line:10%
>> There's no way to say
that cell-phone use is safe.

00:14:39.680 --> 00:14:41.390 align:middle line:10%
The public generally
assumes that,

00:14:41.390 --> 00:14:44.210 align:middle line:10%
if one is selling
something on the market,

00:14:44.210 --> 00:14:48.850 align:middle line:10%
that we have had assurances
that that device is safe.

00:14:48.850 --> 00:14:56.010 align:middle line:90%


00:14:56.010 --> 00:15:00.660 align:middle line:10%
>> When cell phones first
came into consumer use,

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:05.790 align:middle line:10%
the purpose was to carry the
signal wirelessly only a little

00:15:05.790 --> 00:15:09.150 align:middle line:10%
ways and then to convert
the signal to the wired

00:15:09.150 --> 00:15:11.440 align:middle line:10%
infrastructure that we
had on landline, you know,

00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:12.240 align:middle line:10%
phone lines.

00:15:12.240 --> 00:15:17.790 align:middle line:84%
But, when we began the process
of moving to digital signal,

00:15:17.790 --> 00:15:22.280 align:middle line:84%
we had to have a different
kind of infrastructure.

00:15:22.280 --> 00:15:24.240 align:middle line:84%
So, recently, in the
past year or two,

00:15:24.240 --> 00:15:27.350 align:middle line:84%
there has been a lot more cell
towers popping up and down,

00:15:27.350 --> 00:15:28.860 align:middle line:90%
all over the place.

00:15:28.860 --> 00:15:31.220 align:middle line:84%
So there's the existing
one, right there.

00:15:31.220 --> 00:15:32.870 align:middle line:90%
Not sure whose it is.

00:15:32.870 --> 00:15:34.360 align:middle line:90%
So there she is, right there.

00:15:34.360 --> 00:15:35.450 align:middle line:90%
Thar she blows.

00:15:35.450 --> 00:15:38.110 align:middle line:90%


00:15:38.110 --> 00:15:41.830 align:middle line:84%
>> In 1985, the total number of
cell-phone towers in the United

00:15:41.830 --> 00:15:44.700 align:middle line:90%
States stood at just 900.

00:15:44.700 --> 00:15:49.110 align:middle line:84%
Today, that figure
stands north of 215,000.

00:15:49.110 --> 00:15:54.566 align:middle line:90%
[HUMMING/BUZZING]

00:15:54.566 --> 00:16:12.950 align:middle line:90%


00:16:12.950 --> 00:16:17.440 align:middle line:84%
>> What ended up happening was
that the infrastructure that

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:22.060 align:middle line:84%
would be required to
deliver cell phone signals,

00:16:22.060 --> 00:16:25.780 align:middle line:84%
and later Wi-Fi, had to be
spread all across the country,

00:16:25.780 --> 00:16:27.924 align:middle line:90%
in what was called "cells."

00:16:27.924 --> 00:16:30.090 align:middle line:84%
That's why they call them
"cell phones," by the way.

00:16:30.090 --> 00:16:31.640 align:middle line:90%
It looks sort of like a beehive.

00:16:31.640 --> 00:16:34.540 align:middle line:84%
So that every cell was like
one of those little circles

00:16:34.540 --> 00:16:35.830 align:middle line:90%
in a beehive.

00:16:35.830 --> 00:16:38.200 align:middle line:84%
And what would happen
is that the signal

00:16:38.200 --> 00:16:40.060 align:middle line:90%
would go to a base station.

00:16:40.060 --> 00:16:43.600 align:middle line:10%
And then, as long as you were
within the cell, on your phone,

00:16:43.600 --> 00:16:46.299 align:middle line:10%
that cell tower would
be handling your call.

00:16:46.299 --> 00:16:48.090 align:middle line:84%
But as soon as you
moved into another cell,

00:16:48.090 --> 00:16:52.600 align:middle line:84%
it would hand off the signal
to the next cell tower.

00:16:52.600 --> 00:16:56.080 align:middle line:10%
And that required
an infrastructure

00:16:56.080 --> 00:17:00.790 align:middle line:10%
so that there's always a
transmission-and-reception loop

00:17:00.790 --> 00:17:04.480 align:middle line:10%
between the cell phone and the
infrastructure or the closest

00:17:04.480 --> 00:17:05.619 align:middle line:10%
base station.

00:17:05.619 --> 00:17:10.790 align:middle line:84%
That's also how the base
station knows where you are.

00:17:10.790 --> 00:17:14.450 align:middle line:10%
If you have good
signals in Maryland

00:17:14.450 --> 00:17:17.690 align:middle line:10%
but you don't have good
signals in Virginia,

00:17:17.690 --> 00:17:22.280 align:middle line:10%
Maryland would have a commercial
advantage in business.

00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:23.810 align:middle line:90%
It's about fairness.

00:17:23.810 --> 00:17:25.670 align:middle line:84%
And, when you go back
to our Constitution,

00:17:25.670 --> 00:17:29.840 align:middle line:84%
the Commerce Clause is one
of the big fairness clauses.

00:17:29.840 --> 00:17:33.680 align:middle line:84%
So it became a federal
program to build out

00:17:33.680 --> 00:17:36.710 align:middle line:90%
the infrastructure.

00:17:36.710 --> 00:17:40.460 align:middle line:84%
That was the rationale for
the federal government being

00:17:40.460 --> 00:17:43.610 align:middle line:84%
able to come in and, in
effect, in some cases step

00:17:43.610 --> 00:17:45.650 align:middle line:84%
on the rights of
individual citizens,

00:17:45.650 --> 00:17:47.609 align:middle line:84%
in order to build out
the infrastructure.

00:17:47.609 --> 00:17:52.660 align:middle line:90%


00:17:52.660 --> 00:17:54.877 align:middle line:90%
It's our system.

00:17:54.877 --> 00:17:57.210 align:middle line:84%
>> Everyone told us, you're
not going to be able to win.

00:17:57.210 --> 00:17:58.190 align:middle line:90%
You're not able to fight.

00:17:58.190 --> 00:17:59.190 align:middle line:90%
There's nothing you can do.

00:17:59.190 --> 00:17:59.540 align:middle line:90%
It's done.

00:17:59.540 --> 00:18:00.110 align:middle line:90%
It's going up.

00:18:00.110 --> 00:18:00.949 align:middle line:90%
It's happening.

00:18:00.949 --> 00:18:02.990 align:middle line:84%
And I said to myself, if
and when it does go up I

00:18:02.990 --> 00:18:05.400 align:middle line:84%
want to be able to look at it
and at least say to myself,

00:18:05.400 --> 00:18:06.200 align:middle line:90%
I tried.

00:18:06.200 --> 00:18:07.520 align:middle line:90%
>> We had, like, 10 days, so--

00:18:07.520 --> 00:18:09.680 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, and I ran around for
a week, couple hours a night,

00:18:09.680 --> 00:18:10.721 align:middle line:90%
trying to get signatures.

00:18:10.721 --> 00:18:14.960 align:middle line:84%
Then we got enough to go to City
Hall, get our foot in the door.

00:18:14.960 --> 00:18:18.740 align:middle line:10%
>> My message was that if
these cell towers were not safe

00:18:18.740 --> 00:18:21.770 align:middle line:10%
enough for the fire department
to have them where they live

00:18:21.770 --> 00:18:26.450 align:middle line:10%
and work, then why is it safe
enough to have near 3,000

00:18:26.450 --> 00:18:29.480 align:middle line:10%
children who go to school and
live in the immediate area.

00:18:29.480 --> 00:18:33.030 align:middle line:90%


00:18:33.030 --> 00:18:36.990 align:middle line:84%
That's how it came to pass that
we were able to stop the tower.

00:18:36.990 --> 00:18:38.790 align:middle line:84%
>> I live and breathe
by this technology.

00:18:38.790 --> 00:18:40.360 align:middle line:84%
I want to watch something
while stuck in the car.

00:18:40.360 --> 00:18:42.780 align:middle line:84%
I want to be able to justify
being stuck in traffic

00:18:42.780 --> 00:18:44.820 align:middle line:84%
and call my mom or
grandma on the phone.

00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:48.390 align:middle line:84%
>> It's a typical human thing,
that we have new technology,

00:18:48.390 --> 00:18:51.060 align:middle line:84%
we get very excited about it, we
use it, we push it really far,

00:18:51.060 --> 00:18:53.500 align:middle line:90%
and it has great applications.

00:18:53.500 --> 00:18:55.650 align:middle line:84%
However, many of
those often come

00:18:55.650 --> 00:18:57.250 align:middle line:90%
with health considerations.

00:18:57.250 --> 00:19:01.230 align:middle line:84%
And so, once those
become more evident

00:19:01.230 --> 00:19:03.390 align:middle line:84%
to the general population,
then we hopefully

00:19:03.390 --> 00:19:04.920 align:middle line:84%
force the government
and scientists

00:19:04.920 --> 00:19:09.420 align:middle line:84%
to come up with a safer way
of using that technology.

00:19:09.420 --> 00:19:12.200 align:middle line:84%
>> Today our world is
being remade, yet again,

00:19:12.200 --> 00:19:15.700 align:middle line:84%
by an information revolution,
changing the way we work,

00:19:15.700 --> 00:19:18.836 align:middle line:84%
the way we live, the way
we relate to each other.

00:19:18.836 --> 00:19:20.210 align:middle line:84%
With the stoke of
a pen, our laws

00:19:20.210 --> 00:19:22.671 align:middle line:90%
will catch up with our future.

00:19:22.671 --> 00:19:25.560 align:middle line:10%
[APPLAUSE]

00:19:25.560 --> 00:19:30.480 align:middle line:10%
>> In 1995 and 1996, we
began the process of a new

00:19:30.480 --> 00:19:32.670 align:middle line:10%
telecommunications.

00:19:32.670 --> 00:19:37.080 align:middle line:10%
And the Telecommunications Act,
now, was, for the first time,

00:19:37.080 --> 00:19:42.420 align:middle line:10%
written to put the FCC in the
role of a policing agency.

00:19:42.420 --> 00:19:46.170 align:middle line:84%
But the FCC's job,
as a commission,

00:19:46.170 --> 00:19:48.930 align:middle line:84%
was fair and equitable
use of spectrum.

00:19:48.930 --> 00:19:51.960 align:middle line:84%
The FCC was not a policing
agency, had nothing

00:19:51.960 --> 00:19:55.230 align:middle line:84%
to do with safety, had nothing
to do with monitoring-- only

00:19:55.230 --> 00:19:57.990 align:middle line:84%
to make sure that the different
phone companies didn't

00:19:57.990 --> 00:19:59.200 align:middle line:90%
cheat each other.

00:19:59.200 --> 00:20:00.960 align:middle line:84%
That's an important
point, because it

00:20:00.960 --> 00:20:05.010 align:middle line:84%
was the industry that lobbied
to have those changes made.

00:20:05.010 --> 00:20:07.770 align:middle line:84%
>> Recognizing the
regulatory void that existed,

00:20:07.770 --> 00:20:10.560 align:middle line:84%
the cellular industry
strategically positioned itself

00:20:10.560 --> 00:20:13.320 align:middle line:84%
to be influential in the kind
of research the government would

00:20:13.320 --> 00:20:16.800 align:middle line:90%
be carrying out on its products.

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:20.280 align:middle line:84%
>> So the wireless industry
agreed to put up money from

00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:21.930 align:middle line:90%
the cell-phone industry.

00:20:21.930 --> 00:20:25.500 align:middle line:84%
And an interagency working group
of the United States government

00:20:25.500 --> 00:20:28.050 align:middle line:84%
was put in place to
oversee the work.

00:20:28.050 --> 00:20:32.130 align:middle line:84%
That project was called the
WTR, or Wireless Technology

00:20:32.130 --> 00:20:32.970 align:middle line:90%
Research.

00:20:32.970 --> 00:20:35.490 align:middle line:10%
And that's the program that I
ran, looking into the health

00:20:35.490 --> 00:20:38.770 align:middle line:10%
effects of wireless technology.

00:20:38.770 --> 00:20:41.320 align:middle line:84%
>> Ordinarily, in a
regulatory context,

00:20:41.320 --> 00:20:44.560 align:middle line:84%
new technologies would be tested
extensively before they reached

00:20:44.560 --> 00:20:46.930 align:middle line:84%
the marketplace, in order
to make sure that they

00:20:46.930 --> 00:20:49.570 align:middle line:84%
didn't present any
dangers to consumers.

00:20:49.570 --> 00:20:52.300 align:middle line:84%
In the case of cell phones,
and the wireless industry

00:20:52.300 --> 00:20:55.990 align:middle line:84%
as a whole, this crucial
stage was bypassed.

00:20:55.990 --> 00:20:57.820 align:middle line:84%
This meant the
regulatory agencies

00:20:57.820 --> 00:21:00.851 align:middle line:84%
were forced to rely on
postmarket surveillance.

00:21:00.851 --> 00:21:03.100 align:middle line:10%
>> I think the thing that
surprised me most and really

00:21:03.100 --> 00:21:05.710 align:middle line:10%
kind of caught my attention the
most, which I hadn't realized,

00:21:05.710 --> 00:21:08.710 align:middle line:10%
is that the manufacturers
actually tell people

00:21:08.710 --> 00:21:11.590 align:middle line:10%
in the instruction manual,
which I'd never read,

00:21:11.590 --> 00:21:13.870 align:middle line:10%
not to put the cell
phone against your ear.

00:21:13.870 --> 00:21:16.840 align:middle line:10%
>> The advice in the phone tells
you to keep it off the body,

00:21:16.840 --> 00:21:19.510 align:middle line:10%
because phones are
tested in two positions.

00:21:19.510 --> 00:21:23.080 align:middle line:10%
They are tested next to the
head and next to the body.

00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:24.970 align:middle line:84%
When they're tested
next to the head,

00:21:24.970 --> 00:21:27.010 align:middle line:90%
they're tested with a spacer.

00:21:27.010 --> 00:21:29.260 align:middle line:84%
The industry has
succeeded in getting

00:21:29.260 --> 00:21:33.100 align:middle line:84%
the FCC to accept an approach
where the phone is not

00:21:33.100 --> 00:21:34.260 align:middle line:90%
used like this.

00:21:34.260 --> 00:21:36.710 align:middle line:84%
And you know that this is
exactly how most people use

00:21:36.710 --> 00:21:37.510 align:middle line:90%
phones.

00:21:37.510 --> 00:21:41.290 align:middle line:84%
>> We were sort of caught
in a difficult place,

00:21:41.290 --> 00:21:44.950 align:middle line:84%
because some of the claims that
were being made about health

00:21:44.950 --> 00:21:49.810 align:middle line:84%
effects were so severe that, had
